  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Life saving through rehabilitation of collective shelters and unfinished buildings in Deir-ez-Zor and Raqqa.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">IDPs from Homs and Hama are still displaced in Tabqa and currently located in collective shelters in unfinished buildings. According to NPM, as of November 2017, there are currently around 578,000 IDPs from Hama and 641,000 IDPs from Homs outside those governorates. There are currently around 32,500 individuals from Homs displaced Hassakeh, 2,600 in Raqqa, and 9,700 in Deir-Ez-Zor and, from Hama, around 4,600 Hassakeh and 2,600 Raqqa. There are none or no significant number of IDP from Hama in Deir-Ez-Zor. Those IDPs will be relocated out of Tabqa city if their conditions of living are not improved. Their relocation will be to camps which is not an optimal option. To avoid this potential repeated displacement and to help IDPs with their coping mechanism in Tabqa City, it is essential to rehabilitate, maintain and improve the collective shelters and unfinished buildings in which they are living. In Hassakeh, 19 per cent of IDPs live in unfinished/abandoned buildings and 54 per cent in formal collective shelters. A third of those IDPs live in critical shelters that do not provide adequate conditions are women or minors. Similar situation exists in rural Raqqa and Deir-Ez-Zor families occupying unfinished or public buildings where the minimum standard of shelter needs are not met. In Raqqa, 53 per cent of IDPs live in unfinished/abandoned buildings, and half of IDPs living in critical shelters are women and minors. Therefore UNHCR will intervene to upgrade those collective shelter and unfinished buildings or rehabilitate including partition, communal wash facilities, protection from the elements. All these activities are in line with the shelter guidelines with the collective shelter and unfinished building rehabilitation.</narrative>
  </description>
